{"title":"Pro Log: Egan Bernal gets first win since 2021 Giro; Paris-Roubaix chicane removed; Elisa Longo Borghini wins UAE Tour; Óscar Freire found safe","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pro-cycling-news-egan-bernal-colombian-championships","date":1739206764000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pro-cycling-news-egan-bernal-colombian-championships\">Pro Log: Egan Bernal gets first win since 2021 Giro; Paris-Roubaix chicane removed; Elisa Longo Borghini wins UAE Tour; Óscar Freire found safe</a></p>\n\n<p>Welcome back to another edition of <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/pro-log\">Pro Log</a>. Here’s a rundown of the latest results before we get started:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tour of Oman, Stage 3, Mon 10th Feb:</strong> 1st David Gaudu, Groupama-FDJ, 4h 16min 10sec; 2nd Adam Yates, UAE Team Emirates, +01sec; 3rd Damien Howson, Q36.5 Pro Cycling, +2min 08sec. </li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>UAE Tour Women, Overall, Sun 9th Feb:</strong> 1st Elisa Longo Borghini, UAE Team ADQ, 13h 14min 57sec; 2nd Silvia Persico, UAE Team ADQ, +2min 06sec; 3rd Kim Le Court, AG Insurance Soudal, +00sec. </li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Tour of Oman, Stage 2, Sun 9th Feb:</strong> 1st Louis Vervaeke, Soudal Quick-Step, 4h 45min 06sec; 2nd Valentin Paret-Peintre, Soudal Quick-Step, +02sec; 3rd Sean Flynn, Team Picnic PostNL, +02sec. </li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Volta Comunitat Valenciana, Overall, Sun 9th Feb:</strong> 1st Santiago Buitrago, Bahrain Victorious, 16h 17min 43sec; 2nd João Almeida, UAE Team Emirates, +18sec; 3rd Pello Bilbao, Bahrain Victorious, +39sec.</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Étoile de Bessèges, Overall, Sun 9th Feb:</strong> 1st Kevin Vauquelin, Arkéa B&amp;B Hotels, 13h 20min 40sec; 2nd Dylan Teuns, Cofidis, +1min 22sec; 3rd Kevin Geniets, Groupama-FDJ, +1min 35sec.</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n\n\n<h2>Egan Bernal is back</h2>\n\n\n\n<div><blockquote><p>He always knew he'd get his hands back in the air again <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/14.0.0/72x72/1f64c.png\" alt=\"🙌\" /><br /><br />What an incredible, emotional win for <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Eganbernal?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\" target=\"_blank\">@Eganbernal</a>. Your new Colombian National Road Champion <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/14.0.0/72x72/1f60d.png\" alt=\"😍\" /><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/14.0.0/72x72/1f1e8-1f1f4.png\" alt=\"🇨🇴\" /> <a href=\"https://t.co/TKmUHtNHaf\" target=\"_blank\">pic.twitter.com/TKmUHtNHaf</a></p>— INEOS Grenadiers (@INEOSGrenadiers) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/INEOSGrenadiers/status/1888669591015969143?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\" target=\"_blank\">February 9, 2025</a></blockquote> </div>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s been a long road back to the front of the peloton for Ineos Grenadiers’ Egan Bernal, who suffered life-threatening injuries after a horror training ride crash in 2022, from which he said he had a ‘95% chance’ of either becoming paralysed or dying. Despite this, he incredibly returned to the peloton eight months later. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Three years after the crash, Bernal is finally back to winning ways, winning both the time-trial and road race at the Colombian National Championships – his first victories since he won the Giro d’Italia in May 2021.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/subscriptions?utm_source=Web&amp;utm_medium=Banner&amp;utm_campaign=Banner+5\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"300\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-970x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-970x300.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-300x93.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-768x238.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-1536x476.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-2048x634.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-750x232.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/01/Subs-flash-160-for-web-5-1140x353.jpg 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Paris-Roubaix 2025 routes revealed</h2>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"705\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-705x970.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-705x970.jpg 705w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-218x300.jpg 218w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-768x1056.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1117x1536.jpg 1117w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1489x2048.jpg 1489w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-750x1031.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1140x1568.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Mens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-scaled.jpg 1862w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Paris-Roubaix will take place this year on 12th April (women’s) and 13th April (men’s), and the chicane introduced last year to slow down the approach to the Trouée d’Arenberg in the men’s race has been removed. The <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/paris-roubaix-arenberg-forest\">infamous sector</a> will instead be preceded by a detour alongside a mining site in Arenberg, involving four right-angle corners over a single kilometre to help keep the peloton at a safer speed as it drives towards the forest’s harsh cobbles.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are also two additional cobbled <em>secteurs</em> in the race for 2025: Artes (#24, 1.3km) will be followed by Famars (#23, 1.2km), the latter set to also host a stage finish at the 2025 Four Days of Dunkirk in May. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Overall, the men’s race will be slightly shorter than in 2024 at 259.2km.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><img width=\"697\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-697x970.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-697x970.jpg 697w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-216x300.jpg 216w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-768x1069.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1104x1536.jpg 1104w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1472x2048.jpg 1472w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-750x1044.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025-1140x1586.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/Womens-Paris-Roubaix-route-2025.jpg 1811w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Paris-Roubaix Femmes remains 148.5km and the route is identical to the 2024 edition won by SD Worx-Protime’s Lotte Kopecky.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/women-grand-tour-future-winners\">Who could be the next women’s Grand Tour winner?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/caleb-ewan-ineos-grenadiers\">It’s make or break for Ineos Grenadiers and Caleb Ewan</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/pro-cyclists-on-reality-tv\">The best pro cyclist appearances on reality TV</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/what-does-the-future-look-like-for-ineos-grenadiers\">What does the future look like for Ineos Grenadiers?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Elisa Longo Borghini wins the UAE Tour</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><div></div><img width=\"970\" height=\"646\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-970x646.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2198535973.jpg 1024w\" /><figcaption>Tim de Waele/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The winner of the UAE Tour Women is normally decided on the climb of Jebel Hafeet and this year was no different, as Italian national champion Elisa Longo Borghini took her first win for UAE Team ADQ at the summit finish of Stage 3 by 35 seconds ahead of teammate Silvia Persico, going on to take the overall victory the following day by a 2min 06sec margin over Persico.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Elsewhere, the race’s flat days were dominated by SD Worx-Protime sprinter Lorena Wiebes, who claimed three victories from three.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Óscar Freire found after going missing</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><div></div><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/02/GettyImages-2196312571.jpg 1024w\" /><figcaption>Loic Venance/AFP via Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Óscar Freire has been found safe after his family reported him missing on Monday 3rd February. The three-time world champion, who also won three editions of Milan-San Remo and stages at both the Tour and Vuelta a España, had apparently left home in Torrelavega in northern Spain after returning from the AlUla Tour.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The 48-year-old left after a ‘family problem’ and his car was later discovered. Freire was located two days later and his family has asked for privacy surrounding the matter.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>See you next week.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/newsletters\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"351\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-970x351.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-970x351.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-300x109.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-768x278.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-1536x556.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-2048x741.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-750x271.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/10/Newsletter-flash-2-1140x412.jpg 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/pro-cycling-news-egan-bernal-colombian-championships\">Pro Log: Egan Bernal gets first win since 2021 Giro; Paris-Roubaix chicane removed; Elisa Longo Borghini wins UAE Tour; Óscar Freire found safe</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"Robyn Davidson &#124; Editorial Assistant","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"97162b07eb51fcc119f673325cd87b5b504036f14efc4d6904c18a4cf14f413e","category":"Cycling"}